    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nSimilar to how `z=`, `:tselect`, `:bro oldfiles`, and `:recover` now internally delegate to `vim.ui.select()`, ideally, builtin features that need input should delegate to `vim.ui.input`.\n\nBut `vim.ui.input` may be asynchronous, so such features would not work in mappings or macros. \n\n(p.s. it's a bit weird that `input` may be async. I guess it's useful for completion/validation, or high-level UIs that make network requests... but usually those would use `vim.ui.select()` ? Edit: oh it's used by `vim.lsp.buf.rename()`)\n\nrelated\n\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/12390\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/24632\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nBuiltin features can call `vim._core.xx.input` which decides whether to delegate to `ui.input` depending on the context:\n\n```lua\nfunction vim._core.xx.input(opts, on_confirm)\n  if vim.fn.reg_executing() ~= ''   -- macro replay\n     or vim.fn.reg_recording() ~= ''\n     or vim.fn.getchar(1) ~= 0      -- pending typeahead (incl. mapping rest)\n  then\n    return vim.fn.input(opts, on_confirm)\n  end\n  return vim.ui.input(opts, on_confirm)\nend\n```\n\nDocument guidance for 3P impls of `vim.ui.input`: they should do something similar. Then all callers of `vim.ui.input` don't have to worry about \n\n\nOther ideas:\n\n- (yuck) `vim.ui.input_sync`\n",
    "closed_at": null,
